CSS Selectors & Styling

Question 1: What is a CSS selector? Provide examples of element, class, and ID selectors.
->A CSS selector is used to choose which HTML elements you want to style.
->Types of CSS Selectors

1. Element Selector
-Selects all elements of a given type.
-Styles all <p> tags.
-Example:
p {
  color: blue;
}

2. Class Selector
-Selects elements with a specific class.
-Styles any element with class="box".
-Example:
.box {
  border: 1px solid black;
}

3. ID Selector
-Selects one element with a specific ID.
-Styles the element with id="header".
-Example
#header {
  background-color: gray;
}

Question 2: Explain the concept of CSS specificity. How do conflicts between multiple styles
get resolved?
->CSS specificity is the rule the browser uses to decide which CSS style gets applied when multiple rules target the same element.

| Selector Type      | Example              | Specificity Value |
| ------------------ | -------------------- | ----------------- |
| Universal selector | `*`                  | 0                 |
| Element selector   | `p`, `div`           | 1                 |
| Class selector     | `.box`               | 10                |
| Attribute selector | `input[type="text"]` | 10                |
| Pseudo-class       | `:hover`             | 10                |
| ID selector        | `#header`            | 100               |
| Inline style       | `style=""`           | 1000              |

1.Highest Specificity Wins
->If a <p id="title" class="text"> exists → red wins
->Example:
p { color: blue; }        /* specificity 1 */
.text { color: green; }   /* specificity 10 */
#title { color: red; }    /* specificity 100 */

2.If Specificity Is Equal → Last Rule Wins
->Green wins because it appears later in the CSS.
->Example:
.text { color: blue; }
.text { color: green; }

3.Inline Styles Override Most Rules
->Purple wins (inline style beats class, ID, etc.)
->Example:
<p style="color: purple;" class="text">Hello</p>

4.!important Overrides Everything
->Blue wins, even though ID has higher specificity.
->If two rules both use !important, then specificity is compared again.
->Example:
p { color: blue !important; }
#title { color: red; }

->Inline > ID > Class/Attribute/Pseudo-class > Element
->1000 > 100 > 10 > 1

Question 3: What is the difference between internal, external, and inline CSS? Discuss the
advantages and disadvantages of each approach.
1.Inline CSS
->CSS is written inside an HTML tag using the style attribute.
Advantage: Quick for small changes.
Disadvantage: Not reusable and hard to manage.
Example:
<p style="color: red; font-size: 18px;">Hello World</p>

2.Internal CSS
->CSS is written inside the <style> tag in the HTML file.
Advantage: Styles the whole page.
Disadvantage: Cannot be used on multiple pages.
Example:
<head>
  <style>
    p {
      color: blue;
      font-size: 18px;
    }
  </style>
</head>


3.External CSS
->CSS is written in a separate .css file and linked to HTML.
Advantage: Reusable and easy to maintain.
Disadvantage: Needs an extra file and link.
Example:
<head>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
->styles.css
p {
  color: green;
  font-size: 18px;
}


5. CSS Box Model

Question 1: Explain the CSS box model and its components (content, padding, border,
margin). How does each affect the size of an element?

->In CSS, every HTML element is treated like a rectangular box. The box model describes how the size of that box is calculated and how space is added around content.
->It has four main parts (from inside to outside):
    Content → Padding → Border → Margin

1. Content
->This is the actual text, image, or other data inside the element.
->Controlled by: width and height
->This sets the size of only the content area (by default).
->Example:
div {
  width: 200px;
  height: 100px;
}

2. Padding
->Padding is the space between the content and the border.
->Makes the box bigger inside the border
->Background color extends into padding
->If width = 200px and padding = 20px on both sides:
->Total width so far = 200 + 20 + 20 = 240px
->Example:
div {
  padding: 20px;
}

3. Border
->Border wraps around padding and content.
->If border = 5px on both sides:
->Total width now = 240 + 5 + 5 = 250px
->Example:
div {
  border: 5px solid black;
}

4. Margin
->Margin is the space outside the border, separating the element from other elements.
->Margin does NOT affect the element’s internal size, but it adds space around it.
->Example:
div {
  margin: 15px;
}

*Important: box-sizing
->By default:
box-sizing: content-box; /* padding & border added outside width */
->But if you use:
box-sizing: border-box;

->Then padding and border are included inside the given width and height, making layout easier.

div {
  width: 200px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 5px solid black;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

Question 2: What is the difference between border-box and content-box box-sizing in
CSS?Which is the default?

1.box-sizing: content-box (Default)
->This is the default box model in CSS.
->The width and height you set apply only to the content area
->padding and border are added outside that size
->Total width = 200 + 20 + 20 + 5 + 5 = 250px
->So the element becomes bigger than the width you set.
Formula:
Actual element width = width + padding + border
Example:
div {
  width: 200px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 5px solid black;
  box-sizing: content-box; /* default */
}

2.box-sizing: border-box
->Here, the width and height include content + padding + border
Formula:
Content width = width - padding - border
->Total width = exactly 200px
->The content area shrinks to make space for padding and border.
Example:
div {
  width: 200px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 5px solid black;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

6. CSS Flexbox

Question 1: What is CSS Flexbox, and how is it useful for layout design? Explain the terms
flex-container and flex-item

->CSS Flexbox (Flexible Box Layout) is a layout system in CSS that helps you arrange elements in a row or column and control how they align, space, and resize inside a container.
->It’s super useful because it makes layouts responsive and easy to manage, especially when you want items to automatically adjust their size or position based on screen size.

1.Flex Container
->A flex-container is the parent element where Flexbox is applied.
->You activate Flexbox by adding:
->Once this is set, all direct child elements become flex items.
Example:
.container {
  display: flex;
}
->Here, .container is the flex-container.

2.Flex Item
->A flex-item is any direct child of a flex-container.
->Flex items can:
    Grow or shrink
    Align differently
    Be reordered
    Take up available space dynamically
Example:
<div class="container">
  <div class="box">1</div>
  <div class="box">2</div>
  <div class="box">3</div>
</div>
->Each .box is a flex-item because it’s inside a flex-container.

*Why Flexbox is Useful
->Easy horizontal & vertical alignment
->Space distribution between items
->Responsive without complex positioning
->Works great for navigation bars, cards, forms, and page sections
->In short: Flexbox makes layout design flexible, clean, and responsive

Question 2: Describe the properties justify-content, align-items, and flex-direction used
inFlexbox.

1. flex-direction
->Decides which direction flex items are placed inside the container.
    row (default) – Items go left to right
    row-reverse – Items go right to left
    column – Items go top to bottom
    column-reverse – Items go bottom to top
    It controls the main axis direction.

2. justify-content
->Aligns items along the main axis (the direction set by flex-direction).
->Common values:
    flex-start – Items at the start
    flex-end – Items at the end
    center – Items in the center
    space-between – Equal space between items
    space-around – Space around items
    space-evenly – Equal space everywhere
->Think of it as horizontal alignment when direction is row, and vertical alignment when direction is column.

3. align-items
->Aligns items along the cross axis (perpendicular to main axis).
->Common values:
    flex-start – Align to top (or left in column)
    flex-end – Align to bottom (or right in column)
    center – Align to center
    stretch (default) – Items stretch to fill container
    baseline – Align text baselines
->Think of it as vertical alignment when direction is row, and horizontal alignment when direction is column.

7. CSS Grid

Question 1: Explain CSS Grid and how it differs from Flexbox. When would you use Grid over
Flexbox
->CSS Grid is a layout system that works in two directions — rows and columns at the same time. It is used to design the overall structure of a webpage.
->Flexbox is a layout system that works in one direction only — either a row or a column. It is mainly used to align and space items inside a container.

->Difference Between Grid and Flexbox

| CSS Grid                          | Flexbox                         |
| --------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Two-dimensional (rows + columns)  | One-dimensional (row OR column) |
| Best for full page layouts        | Best for small components       |
| More control over exact placement | Items flow in one direction     |

->Use CSS Grid when you need to design a complete page layout with rows and columns, like:
    Website layouts
    Image galleries
    Dashboards
->Use Flexbox for smaller layouts like menus, buttons, or aligning items in a row.
->In short:
    Grid = Big layout
    Flexbox = Small alignment

Question 2: Describe the grid-template-columns, grid-template-rows, and grid-gap
properties. Provide examples of how to use them.

1.grid-template-columns
->This property defines how many columns your grid has and how wide each column should be.

Example 1: Fixed column sizes
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 200px 200px;
}

Example 2: Using fractions (fr)
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr;
}
->The space is divided into 4 equal parts
->First column = 1 part
->Second column = 2 parts
->Third column = 1 part
->Great for responsive layouts.

Example 3: Auto-fit with minimum size
->Creates as many columns as fit, each at least 150px, and stretches them evenly.
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(150px, 1fr));
}

3.grid-template-rows
->This works just like columns, but controls the height of rows.
Example
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-rows: 100px 200px auto;
}
->Creates 3 rows:
    Row 1 = 100px
    Row 2 = 200px
    Row 3 = takes remaining space automatically

Using fr for rows

.container {
  height: 500px;
  display: grid;
  grid-template-rows: 1fr 2fr;
}
->The total height (500px) is split into 3 parts
    First row = 1 part
    Second row = 2 parts

3.grid-gap (now called gap)
->This property adds space between rows and columns.
Example: Same gap for rows & columns
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  grid-gap: 20px;
}
->Adds 20px space between all rows and columns

->Different gap for rows and columns
    Row gap = 10px
    Column gap = 30px
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 10px 30px; /* row-gap column-gap */
}

8. Responsive Web Design with Media Queries

Question 1: What are media queries in CSS, and why are they important for responsive
design?
->Media queries in CSS are a way to apply different styles based on a device’s characteristics — like screen width, height, resolution, or orientation.
->They are a core part of responsive web design, which means making websites look good on mobiles, tablets, laptops, and large screens.

*What Are Media Queries?
->A media query uses the @media rule to check conditions about the device, then applies CSS only if those conditions are true.
->This means: If the screen width is 600px or less (like a phone), change the background color.
Syntax:
@media (condition) {
  /* CSS rules here */
}

Example:

@media (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}

*Why Are Media Queries Important for Responsive Design?
->Because users browse websites on different screen sizes, one fixed layout won’t work everywhere. Media queries let us adapt.

1. Adjust Layout for Different Screens
->On larger screens, elements can sit side-by-side. On small screens, they stack.

Example:
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    display: flex;
  }
}

2. Improve Readability
->Smaller text might fit better on small devices.

Example:
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  body {
    font-size: 14px;
  }
}

3. Optimize Navigation
->Full menu for desktop, hamburger menu for mobile.

Example:
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .menu {
    display: none;
  }
  .hamburger {
    display: block;
  }
}

4. Handle Device Orientation
Example:
@media (orientation: landscape) {
  body {
    background-color: lightgreen;
  }
}


| Feature                  | What It Checks         |
| ------------------------ | ---------------------- |
| `width`, `height`        | Screen size            |
| `min-width`, `max-width` | Responsive breakpoints |
| `orientation`            | Portrait or landscape  |
| `resolution`             | Screen pixel density   |


Question 2: Write a basic media query that adjusts the font size of a webpage for screens smaller than 600px.

->Here’s a simple media query for that:

Example:
/* Default font size for larger screens */
body {
  font-size: 18px;
}

/* Smaller screens (less than 600px wide) */
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    font-size: 14px;
  }
}

->This reduces the font size when the screen width is 600px or less, making text fit better on small devices like phones.

9. Typography and Web Fonts

Question 1: Explain the difference between web-safe fonts and custom web fonts. Why
might you use a web-safe font over a custom font?

1.Web-Safe Fonts
->Web-safe fonts are fonts that are already installed on most operating systems and devices.

Examples:
Arial, Verdana, Times New Roman, Georgia, Courier New

->Key Points:
    No need to download anything
    Load instantly
    Look consistent across most devices
    Very reliable for performance

2.Custom Web Fonts
->Custom web fonts are fonts that are not pre-installed on users' devices. They are loaded from the web using CSS like @font-face or services like Google Fonts.

Examples:
Roboto, Open Sans, Lato, Montserrat

->Key Points:
    More creative and unique design options
    Must be downloaded when the page loads
    Can slightly slow down page performance
    May not display if font files fail to load

->Why Use a Web-Safe Font Instead of a Custom Font?
->You might choose a web-safe font when:
    Speed matters – No font download = faster page load
    Better compatibility – Works on almost all devices
    Low bandwidth users – Helpful where internet is slow
    Simplicity – No extra font hosting or setup needed
    Reliability – No risk of font failing to load

Question 2: What is the font-family property in CSS? How do you apply a custom Google
Font to a webpage?

1. What is the font-family property in CSS?
->The font-family property in CSS specifies the typeface (font) that should be used for the text on a webpage. It can include:
    Specific font names (like "Arial", "Times New Roman")
    Generic font families (like serif, sans-serif, monospace)
    A list of fonts, where the browser uses the first available font

Example:
p {
    font-family: "Arial", sans-serif;
}
->This means: Use Arial if available; otherwise, use any default sans-serif font.

2. How to apply a custom Google Font to a webpage

Step 1: Choose a font from Google Fonts
Step 2: Include the font in your HTML <head> using a <link> tag:

<head>
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
</head>

Step 3: Use the font in CSS with font-family:

body {
    font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;
}

->This will apply the Roboto font to the body text. You can list a fallback font (like sans-serif) in case Google Fonts fails to load.
